metadata.name: WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition #36
metadata.description:
WTBS: Olympics Poster Edition is our official collaboration with Jeres, who was kind enough to work with us in support of the show. The project leans into classic Olympic poster design motifs, embellished by Jeres' signature approach to color and shape. Huge thanks to Jeres for donating their time and enthusiasm to this one, we hope you enjoy it!

As with all WTBS projects, your minting will directly support the podcast and keep us going (and more importantly, collecting!). Our goal is to keep the show free from ads and fully supported by the community, your donations and contributions continue to make that possible. Thank you in advance to everyone who chooses to mint!

Jeres: I love vintage posters. When going to second-hand shops, flea markets or wherever people are selling their used goods, I‚Äôm always on the lookout for what people used to hang on their walls. Bauhaus-inspired posters, socialist propaganda, Nagel prints, anything art deco, etc.. but whenever I come across something Olympics inspired I always feel like I hit pay dirt. There‚Äôs something about the clean, simple design being used to show people coming together along with the undertones of human excellence that just feels special. And circles. I love circles. I hope you enjoy this collection as much as I enjoyed putting it together with Trinity and Will.

Approximate rarity notes:
5%: Gold Edition
10%: Silver Edition
15%: Bronze Edition 

Commands in fullscreen mode:
S : Save current resolution
1 : Save 2000x3000px
2 : Save 4000x6000px
3 : Save 6000x9000px
4 : Save 8000x12000px
5 : Save 10000x15000px

(The higher the resolution, the longer it takes to render/save. use Chrome for best results.)

metadata.name: Highly influential #36
metadata.description:
A few days ago i read an article in which it said that Leonardo da Vinci was a "scientist" and that he devised inventions that "changed the world".

At that moment i thought: "how would it be to make a generative art sketch of a machine invented by da Vinci?"

I don't know how well it turned out, but i hope you like it.

metadata.name: Deep Quartz Cavern #8
metadata.description: Since ancient times, these mystic crystal caverns in the depth of the Earth would bless their owner with wealth. The owner would sell crystal pendants with all kinds of made up magical powers, like healing, throwing fireballs or duck polymorph.

metadata.name: The Modern Depth #8
metadata.description:
there is a new horizon that shimmers and shines

a place which never was before, but there always seemed to be. 
You can see it from the top of any slope, or at the bottom any hole; you can feel it in your bones when you're tired, or be blinded by it when its bright. 
And this is why we must climb every mountain and how we'll map out all those stars. 
A shape made from Modern Depth, standing tall in front of us all.
And all the people that see it on a walk in the woods don't flinch,
they feel a strange connection to the Modern Depth that can be found. 
And most importantly, we don't abuse it because we know how to use it. ¬†

metadata.name: Abstract Hedonism #64
metadata.description:
Abstraction is the beauty of pure geometry and mathematics.

That project was inspired by fathers of minimalism and suprematism, such as the : El Lissitzky, Kazimir Malevich, Pit Mondrian, Paul Klee, etc.

My main goal was to learn how to work with Perlin noise, implement it in different formats and compositions.

Project contains:

‚Ä¢Various formats and orientations of the canvas: from 100 to 1900 pixels
‚Ä¢Carefully selected color palettes with rare BLACK ones
‚Ä¢Fully random animation
‚Ä¢Press "s" to save .png


Made in P5.js by @Georginerous
